Hungary Stocks Rise, Led by Magyar Telekom, Egis, After Slump

-- B y   A n d r a s   G e r g e l y
-- 
2011-04-13T16:11:52Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-13/hungary-stocks-snap-three-days-of-losses-magyar-telekom-rises.html
Hungarian shares advanced from the
biggest decline in four months as three stocks gained for every
one that fell. Magyar Telekom Nyrt. and Egis Nyrt. led gains.  The benchmark BUX stock index rose 0.6 percent to 23,888.5
by the 5 p.m. close in Budapest. The gauge tumbled 2.6 percent
yesterday, the most since November.  Magyar Telekom, the former phone monopoly controlled by
Deutsche Telekom AG, rose 2 percent to 608 forint. Shareholders
yesterday approved a dividend payment of 50 forint per share
after 2010 profit.  Egis, the drugmaker owned by Laboratoires Servier, jumped
1.9 percent, the most since March 9, to 19,195 forint.  Hungary plans to reduce spending on drugs by 120 billion
forint in part by raising a special tax on pharmaceutical
companies to 18 percent from 12 percent, Economy Minister  Gyorgy Matolcsy  told reporters today.  “The market got the announcement that met expectations and
earlier leaks,” Balint Hada, head of research at Quaestor Zrt.
in Budapest, said by phone. The extent of the tax increase
matched a report in newspaper Napi Gazdasag two days ago.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Andras Gergely in Budapest 
